segments.text: Okay, this is a continuation of the interview.
Mary Hicks was the first one.
She was the first one.
The second was Mrs. William Kirksey, K-I-R-K-S-E-Y.
We were extremely important to Mrs. Kirksey in that she had been an army
librarian.
She was a graduate of Peabody College in Tennessee and extremely well trained.
Her husband was a captain with 12 years service who was presently in veterinary school.
Mrs. Kirksey applied at the main library and about the time Mrs. Hicks turned in her resignation,
So we had a second well-trained librarian.
During Mrs. Kirksey's tenure, the library was moved from the main campus to the site west of the tracks where it is still located.
There was no money, or at least Mr. House, the librarian, said there was no money for extra help.
So the various departments paid student labor for a short time.
And then Mr. House decided that the main library could
take over payment of student labor.
So it was a welcome help for Mrs. Kirksey and served the additional purpose that many students were acquainted with library procedure who otherwise would not have been able to.
Following Mrs. Kirksey, who left when her husband graduated,
Incidentally, they are now located in Fort Worth, where he's a successful practitioner.
We've had several well-trained librarians up and into and including the present.
The advent of the medical school here
gave the veterinary library an enormous boost.
And its name was changed from the Veterinary Medical Library to the Medical Resources Library.
Gave it an enormous boost in which way?
In demand on it and demand for services, I should say.
It is now, as I am almost sure, still known as the Medical Resources Library, which includes Budner Medicine as well as Bowles College of Medicine.
And that's about all there is to it.
We just started from tall and built up.
Right, right.
And on the committee, you were basically in charge of the relationship between the university's libraries and the School of Vet Medicine.
Yes.
And also probably ordering books and things like that.
Well, I rubber-stamped them, but I wasn't questioned.
Our book orders primarily came from demand or request by student faculty, and if this fellow is an annoyed student,
expert in the field, who would I be to question it?
So it was a matter of rubber stamping.
Occasionally, we'd have some of the students want to bring in things, for example, like newspapers or whatnot, or fiction.
We thought that was a part of the main library.
In other words, we kept a pretty close touch on what was really
should belong in the veterinary library over in the main library.
We had no intentions of expelling a student because you walked into the main library.
In fact, we encouraged them to go over there.
And Mr. House was extremely sympathetic to the veterinary library.
And when he found that we in the veterinary library end of it fucked the way we did about the main library, we had no trouble.
We were parallel rather than competitive.
Now I would imagine that the budget that you had to buy books grew tremendously.
Yeah, primarily because, you know, a librarian lives by statistics.
Any librarian.
If you got a library with 10,000 books there and nobody used it, you're in a pretty bad way.
So as the use increased and demand for books increased, of course the budget increased.
And the budget went through the main library.
We were a part of Cushing Memorial Library.
Now, were there any other committees that you served on for a time like this?
What were the most important ones, or what would you consider the most important, and let's talk about those and your duties on those.
Well, I was 15 years on the Veterinary Library Committee.
I was 20 years on the Annual Conference for Veterinarians, which is no longer held.
Why isn't that held?
This is a national conference?
No, it was statewide.
It's no longer held for two reasons.
First, the AVMA, I mean the TVMA, the Texas Veteran Medical Association, wanted to move their meetings around.
It started here way back there when Dr. Francis was here.
This was the focus of all meetings.
For years, all the Texas Veterinary Medical Association meetings were held at College Station.
And then they started holding the winter meetings.
And rather than the strict business meeting, the meeting at College Station evolved into a conference or seminar type meeting.
And then as the state grew in number of veterinarians,
And as the number of students grew here, we thought it would be wise to discontinue it and turn it over entirely to the Texas Veterinary Medical Association and be their responsibility.
But it served a need through the years, the war years and on through.
Well, why wasn't it continued then?
I don't know exactly, except that, as I said, there was a phenomenon known as continuing education, which reared its head.
And these continuing education seminars were held various places through a various time of year, and it pretty well superseded the purpose of the conference as such.
Okay, what other main committees?
Well, of course, I was on the selection committee five long years.
And what were your duties there?
Trying to figure out who was lying to me and who wasn't when they said you only wanted to be a veterinarian.
In other words, selected students.
Yes.
That was a no good job.
Why not?
How would you like to pick out 60 boys out of 300 and say that you're in and you're out?
Yeah.
It was no good.
We stayed out there night after night.
And then it got to big that we couldn't have personal interviews, so they... Oh, you had personal interviews to begin with?
Yes.
Until when did you stop?
Oh, I don't remember, but stopped about the time I went off the board.
But then we went over their academic list and threw out those that were hopelessly no good.
I mean, ineligible, I wouldn't say they were no good, but they were maybe too old or maybe they had a sorry academic record or various other things.
And then they started interviewing those who might possibly have a chance.
So I don't know.
I don't know, I haven't been on it for 25 years now.
You were on it back in the 1940s?
Yeah, when it first started.
When Dr. Dunn was dean and later when Dr. Boughton was dean.
Dean at that time was chairman of the selection committee.
Then he got smart and assigned it to a faculty member so he wouldn't catch the flake.
How long were your interviews with each one of these students back in the 1940s?
We'd try to take 10 a night.
10 interviews a night?
Give them about 20 minutes, I guess.
I know we'd get out there at 7, 8, or 12.
And how many would interview?
Well, there were always five of us there.
We interviewed in a group.
This one little old boy would come in and meet five staff at church there.
And if he knew anything at all, he usually was scared out of him before he started.
But I remember one time, one of the interviewers asked an applicant, were you in the service?
He said, yes, sir.
He said, what branch of the Army were you in?
The guy said, the Marines, sir, not Army.
So things like that.
We'd try to get acquainted with them, find out if they knew any veterinarians and why they wanted to be a veterinarian.
Of course, we knew the answer to that, because they'd always wanted to be a veterinarian.
What are you supposed to do after you're out?
Go back to my hometown and practice.
Will you be large animals or small?
They'd all say large animals, so a lot of it was just routine questions.
The main idea just kind of tied them up as the type of boy.
general overall appearance and cleanliness and neatness.
Of course, that was sort of a deal, too, because anybody would be stupid that wouldn't get a haircut and shave before they went in to interview.
But we did the best we could, and I'm sure we turned down some very good boys, but we had the consolation of we didn't let many in that didn't make the grade.
And that was our main deal, was to not waste
placed on somebody who wouldn't make it.
Well, I would imagine that your attrition rate was very low.
It is.
It was and is.
Oh, they drop out because of illness or unavoidable accidents or things, but, and the attrition rate of graduate veterinarians is really low.
The veterinary profession, as such, don't lose near as many
from their ranks to even the MDs.
Really?
That's right.
Once you're a veterinarian, you're usually... How can you account for that?
I can't account for it.
I'm just telling you a fact.
That's really an interesting fact.
It is really interesting.
I thought it would probably be pretty close for both veterinarians and MDs.
Well, I don't know now in 19...
In the 1960s.
Yeah.
Okay.
Now, how about some other committees that you served on?
No, I don't remember.
After all, when you've been there 31 years, you've served on practically every committee.
Okay, okay.
We tried to rotate committees around.
I was on the library committee and the chairman of the conference along with me.
The Library Committee is 15 years to a day and the Congress Committee was 20 years.
And I've been on the curriculum with him from time to time and on various other things, but he has had a department and being there that long while I
had a chance, most committed one time or another.
Right.
Okay, now I have another question.
With the growth of the number of veterinarians, there are also a rapid growth of the number of people in the professional staff, especially after the Second World War.
Yes.
And I was wondering what impact these professional staff members had on the College of, or School of Veterinarian Medicine.
I don't understand, what do you mean impact?
I think it's tend to upgrade it.
We had our first, as I remember, DVM was also PHDs along about that time.
And I also remember that along about the 1950s
Maybe in the 60s we had our first PhDs without the DVM for things like, as I mentioned, biology, bacteriology, and so forth.
OK. We've talked about quite a few changes in the School of Veterinarian Medicine.
What have I missed?
I think you've covered it pretty good.
Is there anything else?
I mean, we've talked about the specialization, the broader curriculum, women, and increasing number of students and research and faculty and enrollment.
Is there something else that we should, do you think that perhaps you had a role in something else that you think that we should?
No, I think I covered it pretty well.
Okay, then as a final question, would you mind just reflecting on the service that you had here at Texas A&M?

What do you think some of the accomplishments or high points you had were, and what do you think some of the things, I don't want to call them low points, but some of the things that you feel that could have been done better?
Well, this is the high point, of course.
I mean, as far as
Oh yeah, that's beautiful.
And when did you receive the Faculty Distinguished Achievement Award?
It's on the back.
On the back of the watch.
Well, one of the
things that always bothered us, of course, was actually lack of money.
Like I said, we were always a day late and a dollar short.
And I was a one-man department through the war years.
Sure.
And then we got a little money and we were able to get technicians to actually prepare the specimen instead of having to go back at night and do it yourself.
And the highlights were that

My dad sold insurance, my mother talked all the time, so I had to get the jab, and I was quite interested in veterinary parasitology, and I was invited to talk at various state meetings across the United States, and I've been in
at all the veterinary colleges that were established at that time.
And I guess the high point was when I got to go to Germany to the International Veterinary Medical Association to give a paper on parasites of the horses.
Really?
When was that?
That sounds fascinating.
When was I in Germany, honey?
I don't remember, 1950s or early 60s.
And then I have been on other international veterinary programs.
I went to Mexico City and went to 1950 in Lima, Peru.
And I enjoyed those, first because I got my expenses paid.
Sure, and you got to see part of the world.

The one thing that I did that was probably pretty well among the first at Texas A&M, now at the commonplace, was that I got a leave of absence and got to go to Peru to help establish the experiment station for the Peruvian government.
And I was down there one semester in 1954.
Really?
And they didn't have any type of experiment?
Oh, they had one, but they wanted to pattern it out in the United States, and I helped set up the operators.
They did the operation as well as they could, but that had a lot of frustrations because it was a whole lot like dropping a die into a fast-running brook.
You could see it cover for a minute and then it'd be gone.
You mean the Peruvians didn't have the training, or what were the problems?
Both, and it's just a type of personality, for example.
Peruvians, I guess like many Spanish-Americans, pretty much a family unit.
So they were on the personnel of an experiment station.
There were several families.
Consequently, there were several kids.
And these kids made pets out of the animals.
They'd take a corn cob and go up to a big bramble bull and rub him.
He'd lay down until you rub him all over.
And one morning, a big bull had through arms in his ear.
And I was going to treat it.
And the chute was just made out of actually flimsy wood.
And I said, we better put a rope on him and put it around this tree.
That chute won't hold him.
And they just laughed.
Oh, El Toro was gentle.
Well, I reached up and grabbed his store here, and he exploded, and little pieces of chute went everywhere.
And he trod off.
He was gentle, but he just didn't like to be handled.
So I said, well, let's get a rope on the tree.
And they said, oh, well, we can do that tomorrow.
And that's the way it was all the time.
And I had a little boy help me get fecal samples to examine for evidence of parasitism.
And I couldn't make him understand why he should wash his hands between each sample.
So I wouldn't get the samples mixed up.
He said, they're already dirty.
Why wash them?
In other words, that was it.
There was a cultural and a language gap then, both.
But I felt like I did a little good.
Who knows?
I've always wanted to go back and see, but never had a chance.
Do we have much of a, does Texas A&M have much of an international program?
Yeah, the school as such does.
I mean the School of Veterinary Medicine.
No.
Mm-hmm.
So in other words, we never bring in foreign students?
Oh yeah, they're sent here.
I'll tell you, you can talk to the international guy out here.
I forget who he's in charge of now.
But we have students from other places, mainly there for advanced degrees.
In fact, I've had several Filipino students that I really, really admired.
I had quite a few Pakistani students that
I didn't think so much of, but kindly.
Why not?
Oh, I don't know.
Their personality is just different.
Oh, I see.
But the Filipinos you got along with.
Oh, yeah.
Why was that?
Well, I don't know.
They're just likeable cousins.
We had a fellow from Ireland come over and stay with us six months.
I don't know what program he was on, whether Ireland was paying for it or whether he was on a state deal.
He was a lot of fun.
Where was he from?
Dublin.
Oh, Dublin.
Robert P. Lee.
He was always butting because if he had known he was going to come here, he'd have changed it to Robert E. Lee.
We had a lot of good fellas.
Is there anything else you think we should discuss?
Oh, I think that ought to close it up.
There's a lot of information I can't give you like foreign students.
Oh, we can get that from other sources.
There's no problem there.
Okay, this ends our interview with Dr. R.D.
Turk.
Thank you very much.
Yes, sir.
